{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ba91f740-e46d-4356-92fd-d8f32c1a581c","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but I can answer from general .NET knowledge:\n\n### Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship with `createdump`. On macOS, use the OS-level crash reporting instead:\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash logs** — macOS automatically writes crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before running:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Core files land in `/cores/` (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n3. **If `/cores/` is missing or permission-denied**, create it:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze the core file** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **For richer .NET diagnostics**, set the environment variable:\n   ```bash\n   export DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\n   export DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/coredump.%p\n   ```\n   However, these rely on the managed runtime's crash handler, which may not be fully available in NativeAOT.\n\n**Key takeaway:** On macOS with NativeAOT, your primary options are Apple's built-in crash logs in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` and OS-level core dumps via `ulimit -c unlimited` + `/cores/`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"de31f1db-8ca7-440c-8ae7-148088f7c50c","outputTokens":413,"requestId":"1B85:1007E7:1644C54:18FCA79:6A02878A"},"id":"1e001580-8f1c-4905-8890-994da5dfc63a","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:51:16.494Z","parentId":"77af2879-4144-4be1-ab59-23025e4379df"}
